g.ns0:text: Rule 0: Constant Rule: $\\frac{d}{dx} a =0$\\\\\nRule I: Sum Rule: $\\frac d {dx} (f+g) = \\frac{d}{dx}f + \\frac{d}{dx} g$\\\\\nRule II: Product Rule: $\\frac d {dx} (fg) = \\frac{df}{dx} g + f \\frac{dg}{dx}$

Rule II.a: Scalar Rule: $\\frac{d}{dx} af = a \\frac{d}{dx} f$ \\\\\n Rule II.b: Power Rule: $\\frac{d}{dx} x^n = n \\frac{d}{dx} x^{n-1}$\\\\\n Rule II.c: Quotient Rule: $\\frac{d}{dx} \\left ( \\frac f g \\right ) = \\frac{\\frac{df}{dx} g - f \\frac{dg}{dx} }{g^2}$
Rule III: Chain Rule: $\\frac{d}{dx} \\left ( f \\circ g \\right ) = (\\frac{df}{dx}\\circ g ) \\frac{dg}{dx}$
Rule III.a: Inverse Rule: $\\frac d{dx} f^{-1} = \\frac{1}{\\frac{df}{dx} \\circ f^{-1}}$
I inflate my spherical balloon with at a rate of $10 \\mbox{ cm}^3/\\mbox{min}$.\\\\\nHow fast is the balloon radius growing when the radius is $5$ cm?
Let $f$ be a function with domain $D$.\\\\\nThe \\emph{critical points} of $f$ are the points $a \\in \\textbf R$\\\\\nwith either $f\'(a)=0$ or $f$ not differentiable at $a$
Local extrema are critical points,\\\\\nbut not all critical points are extrema!

First Derivative Test\\
\\
Let $f$ be differentiable on $(a,b)$ except possibly\\
at critical point $c$. If there is some interval with...\\
\begin{enumerate}
\item $f'$ negative before $c$ but positive after then $f$ has a local min at $c$.
\item $f'$ positive before $c$ but negative after then $f$ has a local max at $c$.
\item $f'$ has the same sign on either side of $c$ then there is no extrema at $c$
\end{enumerate}

$$
f(x)=
\begin{cases}
x+5 & \mbox{ if } x<-2\\
-2x-1 & \mbox{ if } -2 \leq x \leq 0\\
-x-1 & \mbox{ if } 0 \leq x \leq 2\\
3x-9 & \mbox{ if } 2<x
\end{cases}
$$

text.tspan: How many extrema? What type of extrema? Is there an extremest?
